ref: Jour: EPJ Web of Conferences, Vol.66, p.03077 (2014)
title: Measurement of neutron activation cross sections on Mo isotopes in the energy range from 7 MeV to 15 MeV.

x4freetext: Measurement of neutron activation cross sections on Mo
isotopes in the energy range from 7 MeV to 15 MeV.
R.Nolte
V.Semkova

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: EPJ Web of Conferences, Vol.66, p.03077 (2014)

x4freetext: Figures only.
CV28 compact cyclotron operated in
pulse mode, pulse width of about 1 ns, pulse rate
1 MHz during the neutron field characterization and
2 MHz during the sample irradiations.
D(d,n)3He reaction, a gas target of 3cm length
and 1 cm diameter.
Neutron fluence was monitored by both a low-mass 238U
fission chamber and an Al foil mounted in front of the
Mo sample. For each energy point two irradiations with
gas-in and gas-out were carried out and a normalized
gas-out component was subtracted. The measured reaction
rates were further corrected for the contribution of
the breakup neutrons by folding the neutron flux
distribution with the shape of the excitation function
of 238U(n,f), 27Al(n,alpha)24Na or studied reaction.
The measured neutron spectral distribution was compared
with calculated one using Monte Carlo code SINENA.
Cross sections were measured using the neutron
activation method.
The samples consist of elemental Mo with 99.9% purity
in disk-shaped form, 1 mm thick, 10 mm in diameter.
The samples were placed in front of a fission chamber
at zero degree direction relative to the beam axis,
at distance of 6 cm from the centre of the gas cell,
at 15 mm distance from the entrance window of the HPGe
detector.
The mass of the 238U (enriched to 99.98%) deposit
101.6 +- 0.6 microg - used for monitoring.
The radioactivity of the irradiated samples was
measured by an HPGe detector of 300 cm3 and a nominal
efficiency of 70%.
U-238 fission chamber for neutron fluence
monitoring
Corrections were applied for
- the variation of the neutron fluence in time,
- measurement geometry,
- dead time effects,
- coincidence summing effects.
Additional measurement at 135 mm was carried out in
order to determine the corrections for the coincidence
summing effects.
